M365SR03: Excessive Use of Standard Accounts for Administrative Tasks
ISM controls:
•	Control: 0444; Revision: 7; Updated: Sep-23; Applicability: All; OS: All (Technical controls to prevent administrative tasks from being performed by non-privileged accounts)
•	Control: 1175; Revision: 3; Updated: Dec-22; Applicability: All; OS: All (Use of separate accounts for administrative and non-administrative activities)
•	Control: 1507; Revision: 3; Updated: Dec-23; Applicability: All; OS: All (Privileged access to cloud services is performed through a secure gateway or workstation)
________________________________________
Current Risk
The use of standard user accounts to perform administrative activities leading to a tenancy-wide compromise that could disrupt the agency’s SaaS offering resulting in the compromise of confidentiality and integrity of agency systems, data and/or information.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
POSSIBLE	x	MAJOR	=	HIGH
________________________________________
Recommendations:
1.	Enforce Account Separation: Mandate the use of dedicated privileged accounts for all administrative actions, ensuring these accounts have no mailbox and are not used for daily productivity tasks.
2.	Implement Just-In-Time (JIT) Access: Deploy Microsoft Entra Privileged Identity Management (PIM) to provide time-bound, approval-based administrative access.
3.	Secure Administrative Workstations: Require that all administrative activities be conducted from a hardened Privileged Access Workstation (PAW) or a secure management tier.
- Treatment #1
•	Privileged Account Audit: Identify all users currently assigned administrative roles and migrate these permissions to dedicated "admin-only" accounts.
•	Deploy Entra PIM: Configure PIM for all highly privileged roles (e.g., Global Administrator, Intune Administrator), requiring MFA and a business justification for activation.
•	Restrict Admin Access: Update Conditional Access policies to only allow administrative role activation and usage from known, compliant, and managed agency devices.
________________________________________
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
Implementing account separation and JIT access via PIM ensures that administrative privileges are not "always on" and cannot be easily compromised via standard phishing or malware targeting a user's daily account. While a compromise remains a major consequence, the window of opportunity and the complexity required for an attacker to escalate privileges reduces the likelihood to "Rare."
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
RARE	x	MAJOR	=	MEDIUM

